BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Education Programs,Lectures & Talks,Exhibits & Tours,Guided Tour
 s
DESCRIPTION:America 250 Semiquincentennial Programs\n\nExplore North Caroli
 na’s early transportation story through a three-part presentation series he
 ld in conjunction with America 250 Semiquincentennial events taking place t
 hroughout 2026. Scheduled for March\, April\, and May\, the series will hig
 hlight railroad development and construction prior to 1860\, the origins an
 d use of the Nissen wagon\, originally produced in Winston-Salem\, and how 
 supplies were moved during the Revolutionary War.\n\nEach presentation begi
 ns at 7:00 p.m. and will conclude after one hour. This is a free event that
  does not require museum admission\, but all attendees must pre-register fo
 r this presentation. A shuttle bus will be in operation before and after th
 e presentation to transport attendees from parking lot to designated buildi
 ng.\n\n"Wheel Ruts to Iron Rails"\n\nThe development of railroads revolutio
 nized the movement of people and goods across the United States and remains
  a vital chapter in our nation’s story. Discover how early horse-drawn carr
 iages running on metal straps evolved into steam-powered locomotives and ir
 on rails in the late 1820s in England and America. Trace the rapid advancem
 ents in locomotive design from the 1830s through the 1850s\, as expanding r
 ail lines connected the North and South and opened pathways into the wester
 n territories.\n\nThis presentation is hosted by Larry Neal\, who served se
 veral years as a railroad researcher and historian at the North Carolina Tr
 ansportation Museum. If you need assistance or have any questions before re
 gistering\, contact Larry Neal at larry.neal@dncr.nc.gov or 704-636-2889.\n
 \nThis presentation will start in the museum’s Roundhouse Orientation Room 
 and include a brief walk through the building.
DTEND:20260327T000000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030920Z
DTSTART:20260326T230000Z
GEO:35.687243;-80.433348
LOCATION:North Carolina Transportation Museum
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:"Wheel Ruts to Iron Rails" - A250 Presentation
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52198440997242
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/wheel-ruts-to-iron-rails-a250-presenta
 tion
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Education Programs,Lectures & Talks,Panels & Book Discussions,Ce
 lebrations & Commemorations
DESCRIPTION:The Davie County Historical and Genealogical Society will host 
 historian and author Marcia Phillips as she discusses the Regulators Moveme
 nt\, a little-known uprising in the Piedmont Region of North Carolina five 
 years before the outbreak of the American Revolutionary War. With new infor
 mation from her research and insights from her book\, learn how these early
  freedom fighters shaped the outcome of the war.\n\nThe book is titled The 
 Regulator Movement in North Carolina: Prelude to the Revolution.
DTEND:20260327T010000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030920Z
DTSTART:20260326T230000Z
GEO:35.897815;-80.5597
LOCATION:Davie County Public Library\, Multipurpose Room
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Author Speaking Event (Marcia Phillips\; The Regulators Movement) 
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52382415019778
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/author-speaking-event
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Performances & Arts,Theater & Musicals
DESCRIPTION:It’s the summer of 1776\, and the nation is ready to declare in
 dependence… if only our founding fathers can agree to do it! 1776 follows J
 ohn Adams of Massachusetts\, Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania and Thomas J
 efferson of Virginia as they attempt to convince the members of the Second 
 Continental Congress to vote for independence from the shackles of the Brit
 ish monarchy by signing the Declaration of Independence.\n\nThe seminal eve
 nt in American history blazes to vivid life in this most unconventional of 
 Broadway hits. Celebrate the semiquincentennial of the United States at 177
 6!\n\nMusic and Lyrics by Sherman Edwards\nBook by Peter Stone\nBased on a 
 concept by Sherman Edwards\nOriginal Production Directed by Peter Hunt\nOri
 ginally Produced on the Broadway Stage by Stuart Ostrow\n\nDirected by Patr
 ick Torres\n\n1776 is presented through special arrangement with Music Thea
 tre International (MTI). All authorized performance materials are also supp
 lied by MTI. www.mtishows.com\n\nPost-Show Discussion | Sunday\, April 12 @
  6pm\n\nJoin us following the Sunday\, April 12\, matinee performance for a
  post-show discussion. Details coming soon!\n\n \n\nTicket Information\n\nT
 ickets on sale now!\n\nRuntime is approximately 2 hours 45 minutes\, includ
 ing one 15-minute intermission.\n\nShow Times:\n\nFridays and Saturdays (pl
 us Thursday\, April 2) at 8:00pmSundays at 3:00pmSingle ticket prices\, exc
 luding tax and fees:\n\nAdult: $33Senior/Student/Military: $30Seniors are a
 ge 62 and up. Students are through college.
DTSTAMP:20260410T030920Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260327
GEO:35.791719;-78.66886
LOCATION:Raleigh Little Theatre \, Cantey V. Sutton Theatre
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:1776 Musical - Sherman Edwards and Peter Stone
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52435380171030
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/1776-music-sherman-edwards-and-peter-s
 tone
END:VEVENT
