BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Education Programs
DESCRIPTION:Join the Chatham County Historical Association for the Siler Ci
 ty History Club on every second Thursday of the month\, 10:30am-11:30am at 
 First Baptist Church. The Chatham County Historical Association needs your 
 help in learning about the rich and colorful history of Siler City! They ha
 ve facts and figures\, but they need to hear your own memories of Siler to 
 really understand one of Chatham County’s most important cities. Come share
  your memories\, stories\, photos\, mementos\, and other Siler City treasur
 es. Light refreshments will be served. This event is free\, and everyone is
  welcome! No registration is required.\n\nThis event takes place indoors. F
 irst Baptist Church in Siler City is ADA-accessible. No pets allowed. Pleas
 e leave your furry friends at home. Free parking is available next to the c
 hurch.\n\nThis event is part of our Chatham Celebrates America 250 initiati
 ve. See more America 250 events. See more events hosted by The Chatham Hist
 orical Association.
DTEND:20260514T153000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030927Z
DTSTART:20260514T143000Z
GEO:35.726177;-79.463313
LOCATION:First Baptist Church 
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Siler City History Club
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51808526634482
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/siler-city-history-club
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Education Programs,Lectures & Talks
DESCRIPTION:America 250 is not just about what transpired in the U.S.\; it 
 also inspired change globally. This special Sandbar Lecture\, “A Model Revo
 lution: The Global Impact of America’s Independence” is part of the Museum 
 and Planetarium’s celebration of the 250th Anniversary of the signing of th
 e Declaration of Independence.\n\nJoin Ginger R. Davis is the Executive Dir
 ector of the Lower Cape Fear Historical Society\, Latimer House\, and Kella
 m Archive to learn how world revolutions in the 19th and 20th centuries dem
 onstrate how foreign leaders drew upon the examples of Washington and Jeffe
 rson and used documents such as the Declaration of Independence as models f
 or their own statements. The American Revolution was an ideological catalys
 t for global anti-colonialism\, offering a blueprint for self-determination
  that later influenced Asian and African independence movements. It popular
 ized the rhetoric of liberty and natural rights.\n\nAfter 25+ years as a hi
 story professor with specializations in U.S. Foreign Policy\, the Cold War\
 , Vietnamese Studies\, U.S. Military History\, and Black Liberation Studies
 \, Davis is now semi-retired from academia. A Fulbright awardee\, she taugh
 t at Vietnam National University for nearly a decade before returning to he
 r home state of N.C.\, teaching at Duke University and Norwich University\n
 while becoming involved in local historic preservation efforts. She receive
 d her B.A. in History from the University of North Carolina at Wilmington\,
  her M.A. from Texas Tech University\, and her doctorate from Temple Univer
 sity
DTEND:20260514T170000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030927Z
DTSTART:20260514T160000Z
GEO:33.889155;-78.434804
LOCATION:Museum of Coastal Carolina\, Lecture Hall
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Sandbar Lecture Series: A Model Revolution
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52462546200128
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/sandbar-lecture-series-a-model-revolut
 ion
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Education Programs,Youth & Family Activities
DESCRIPTION:Join the Chatham Community Library for It's Elementary: America
  250 Fun and Games hosted on the second Thursday of every month\, 4pm-5pm. 
 Elementary-age kids are invited to explore America's past through a variety
  of crafts and games.\n\nThis FREE\, family-friendly event is open to the p
 ublic. No registration is required. The event will take place indoors in th
 e Chatham Community Library's Holmes Family Meeting Room. The Chatham Commu
 nity Library is ADA-compliant\, including wheelchair-accessible parking\, e
 ntrances\, seating\, common spaces\, walkways\, and restrooms. The Holmes F
 amily Meeting Room has an automatic door opener. Free parking is available 
 outside the library. Pets are not allowed - please leave your furry friends
  at home.\n\nThis event is part of our Chatham Celebrates America 250 initi
 ative. See more America 250 events.
DTEND:20260514T210000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030927Z
DTSTART:20260514T200000Z
GEO:35.723603;-79.188801
LOCATION:Chatham County Library
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:It's Elementary: America 250 Fun and Games
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51774281557388
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/its-elementary-america-250-fun-and-gam
 es
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Performances & Arts
DESCRIPTION:Travel back to 1770s–1780s Cumberland County\, North Carolina\,
  when tensions are rising and the American colonies are on the brink of rev
 olution. In this immersive tabletop role-playing game\, you’ll step into th
 e shoes of local citizens navigating loyalty\, rebellion and survival durin
 g a pivotal moment in history.\n\nExplore real historical events\, regional
  battles and political intrigue as you make choices that shape your story. 
 Will you side with the Patriots\, remain loyal to the Crown or try to survi
 ve somewhere in between?\n\nNo prior role-playing experience is necessary—j
 ust bring your imagination and your sense of adventure.\n\nRegistration is 
 required by calling 910-483-7727\, ext. 1365\, or registering online.
DTEND:20260515T003000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030927Z
DTSTART:20260514T220000Z
GEO:35.044702;-78.937485
LOCATION:Game On! Cards and Coffee
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:TTRPG: Revolutionary Cumberland 
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52267679937351
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/ttrpg-revolutionary-cumberland
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Education Programs,Lectures & Talks,Exhibits & Tours,Guided Tour
 s
DESCRIPTION:America 250 Semiquincentennial Programs\n\nExplore North Caroli
 na’s early transportation story through a three-part presentation series he
 ld in conjunction with America 250 Semiquincentennial events taking place t
 hroughout 2026. Scheduled for March\, April\, and May\, the series will hig
 hlight railroad development and construction prior to 1860\, the origins an
 d use of the Nissen wagon\, originally produced in Winston-Salem\, and how 
 supplies were moved during the Revolutionary War.\n\nEach presentation begi
 ns at 7:00 p.m. and will conclude after one hour. This is a free event that
  does not require museum admission\, but all attendees must pre-register fo
 r this presentation. A shuttle bus will be in operation before and after th
 e presentation to transport attendees from parking lot to designated buildi
 ng.\n\n“History of the Nissen Wagon Works in NC”\n\nNissen Wagon Works bega
 n operation in 1834 and stopped operations in the 1940s. Founded by John Ph
 ilip Nissen\, the company produced many wagons that were used for agricultu
 ral and general transport. Nissen was located near Waughton\, which is now 
 a part of the city of Winston-Salem. Learn about the company and the height
  of production\, which at the time Nissen produced up to 50 wagons daily an
 d became one of the South’s largest manufacturers at the height of producti
 on.\n\nThis presentation is hosted by Larry Neal\, who has served several y
 ears as a historian at the North Carolina Transportation Museum. If you nee
 d assistance or have any questions before registering\, contact Larry Neal 
 at larry.neal@dncr.nc.gov or 704-636-2889.\n\nThis presentation will be hel
 d in the museum’s Back Shop building near the wagon exhibit.
DTEND:20260515T000000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030927Z
DTSTART:20260514T230000Z
GEO:35.687243;-80.433348
LOCATION:North Carolina Transportation Museum
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:History of the Nissen Wagon Works in NC
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52198557938111
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/history-of-the-nissen-wagon-works-in-n
 c
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Education Programs
DESCRIPTION:Pretend you’ve been recruited as a member of the Culper Spy Rin
 g\, and you need to know how to decipher a message written in invisible ink
 . Supplies include a paint brush\, water\, drying cloth\, vitriol (diluted 
 sulfuric acid)\, Thomas Jefferson cipher and “furnace box.” Read the clues 
 to find the coin with a hidden message\, reveal the message using the brush
  and vitriol\, then use the cipher to decode the message.\n\nContact: Nancy
  Locquet Absillis\, nancy.locquet@naturalsciences.org
DTSTAMP:20260410T030927Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260515
GEO:35.782156;-78.639336
LOCATION:North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY: Spy Training 101: Decode a Secret Message
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52504709617318
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/spy-training-101-decode-a-secret-messa
 ge
END:VEVENT
