BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Celebrations & Commemorations,Ceremonies & Anniversaries
DESCRIPTION:Commemorate Independence Day with a reading of Frederick Dougla
 ss' powerful Fourth of July address\, "What to the Slave is the Fourth of J
 uly" at Historic Stagville State Historic Site. \n\nThis is a participatory
  community reading. Every year\, 60 volunteers sign up to read passages fro
 m this famous abolitionist speech in front of the historic slave quarters a
 t Horton Grove. You may sign up as a reader when you arrive. \n\nThis year'
 s reading will mark a special date for reflection and remembrance: the 250t
 h anniversary of the Declaration of Independence. Douglass delivered this p
 owerful speech about freedom and injustice on July 5\, 1852\, at an Indepen
 dence Day celebration in Rochester\, New York. Douglass' speech remains one
  of the most famous abolitionist texts in United States history. The speech
  resonates today\, inviting all to reflect on the United States' founding i
 deals and our shared history of slavery and freedom.\n\nA PDF of the speech
  text will be available via Historic Stagville's website. We suggest you pr
 int or download your own copy to bring to follow along! Some copies will be
  available in person at the event.\n\nBring a chair or blanket to sit on th
 e grounds. The event will be outdoors at the historic slave quarters at Hor
 ton Grove at 5925 Jock Road\, Bahama\, NC 27503. Attendees must walk less t
 han one hundred yards over uneven grass or gravel to reach the reading site
 . Porta-potties will be available on site.\n\nThis free event lasts about 1
  hour\, with the option to view inside the original slave quarters or Great
  Barn at Horton Grove afterwards.
DTEND:20260704T150000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030932Z
DTSTART:20260704T140000Z
GEO:36.115365;-78.841527
LOCATION:Historic Stagville\, Horton Grove
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Frederick Douglass Community Reading at Stagville 
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51844771352480
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/frederick-douglass-community-reading-a
 t-stagville-2025
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Exhibits & Tours,Exhibitions,Performances & Arts,Concerts (Music
 ),Celebrations & Commemorations,Festivals & Fairs,Parades & Community Celeb
 rations,Ceremonies & Anniversaries,Reenactments & Living History,Guided Tou
 rs,Special Site Programs,Education Programs,Youth & Family Activities
DESCRIPTION:Celebrate the Fourth of July at Old Salem!\n\nDid you know the 
 first official Fourth of July Celebration in North Carolina was held in Old
  Salem? In 1783\, Governor Alexander Martin proclaimed July 4th a day of th
 anksgiving and peace\, and Salem residents gathered for food\, fellowship\,
  and festivities. This year\, we invite you to be part of that tradition.\n
 \nJoin us for a full day of music\, history\, and hands-on experiences as w
 e welcome visitors of all ages to commemorate Independence Day at the site 
 of North Carolina’s very first July 4th celebration.\n\nExplore Old Salem M
 useums & Gardens—a historic site sharing the stories of Moravian\, Black\, 
 and Indigenous peoples in the American South. Our museums\, historic town\,
  and gardens offer an immersive and memorable historical experience for all
  visitors.\n\nEvent Highlights\n\nRevolutionary War–Era Music\nHear authent
 ic period music and learn how troops used sound as a communication tool dur
 ing the war. Enjoy worship pieces composed by Moravian musicians—just as Sa
 lem residents did in their weekly services.\n\nHistoric Demonstrations\n• F
 ire Bucket Brigade – Discover how early firefighters managed emergencies be
 fore hand-pumped engines.\n• Historic Firearms – Watch demonstrations of th
 e types of firearms crafted and used in Salem.\n• Frozen Treat Making – Vis
 it the Vogler House to see how early Salem residents created one of America
 ’s favorite sweet treats.\n\nDeclaration of Independence Readings\nJoin us 
 throughout the day for readings of the Declaration of Independence in honor
  of the 250th anniversary of its signing.\n\nGuided Tours\nMeet our costume
 d interpreters and explore the Historic Town of Salem on a guided tour.\n\n
 All activities are included with standard ticket admission. Reserve your sp
 ot today and celebrate the Fourth of July in historic style!
DTEND:20260704T200000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030932Z
DTSTART:20260704T140000Z
GEO:36.083505;-80.24289
LOCATION:Old Salem Museums & Gardens\, Old Salem Visitor Center and the His
 toric District
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Independence Day Celebration at Old Salem
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51499113410036
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/independence-day-celebration-at-old-sa
 lem
END:VEVENT
