BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Celebrations & Commemorations,Ceremonies & Anniversaries
DESCRIPTION:Did you know that North Carolina’s first public reading of the 
 Declaration of Independence took place in Halifax on August 1st\, 1776?  Jo
 in historical interpreters as they reenact events surrounding the joyous ne
 ws of American independence from Britain. At 12:00pm\, see a reenactor port
 ray Cornelius Harnett\, President of the Council of Safety\, read the Decla
 ration for the first time in North Carolina. View a screening of The Americ
 an Constitution\, a new documentary film on the writing of the United State
 s Constitution\, which was partially filmed at Historic Halifax. Free.
DTEND:20260801T220000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030933Z
DTSTART:20260801T140000Z
GEO:36.329317;-77.588638
LOCATION:Historic Halifax
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Independence Comes to NC!
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51586147425438
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/independence-comes-to-nc
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Exhibits & Tours,Exhibitions
DESCRIPTION:March 14 – August 23\, 2026\n\nIn the ultimate battle for survi
 val\, every animal has a plan.\n\nExplore the striking ways nature fights b
 ack in “Staying Alive\,” featuring 17 live animals from around the world wi
 th unbelievable self-defense strategies. Come face to face with trippy toad
 s\, armored armadillos\, a two-toed sloth and more.\n\nDiscover how these d
 efenders deploy an amazing arsenal of high-fashion camouflage and mimicry\,
  specialized armor and advanced chemical warfare – like stink bombs\, caboo
 se cannons and smoke screens – to hide in plain sight\, stand their ground 
 or even drop a limb and make a run for it. Enjoy live animal encounters\, l
 arger-than-life sculptures\, 3D tactile experiences and interactive program
 s.\n\nPerfect for families and animal enthusiasts of all ages. Offered in E
 nglish & Spanish.
DTEND:20260801T210000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030933Z
DTSTART:20260801T140000Z
GEO:35.782156;-78.639336
LOCATION:North Carolina Museum of Natural Sciences
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Staying Alive 
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52207083025706
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/staying-alive
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Celebrations & Commemorations,Reenactments & Living History,Exhi
 bits & Tours,Special Site Programs
DESCRIPTION:Come down to Fort Macon and learn how the different cannons of 
 the fort were loaded\, aimed\, and shot.\n\nCannon firing demonstrations wi
 ll be held at 10:30 a.m.\; 11:30 a.m.\; 1:30 p.m.\; 2:30 p.m.\; and 3:30 p.
 m.\n\n \n\nPhoto by J. Hill: 10-inch mortar demonstration during Labor Day 
 Weekend Cannon Day at Ft. Macon State Park.
DTEND:20260801T193000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030933Z
DTSTART:20260801T143000Z
GEO:34.696366;-76.684506
LOCATION:Fort Macon State Park\, Ft. Macon
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Ft. Macon Cannon Day
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51931025512856
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/ft-macon-cannon-day
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Celebrations & Commemorations
DESCRIPTION:Learn about one of the small arms (musket\, flintlock\, or rifl
 e) that a soldier stationed at Fort Macon would have carried and used.\n\nT
 his will include a blank firing demonstration of the weapon.\nMeet in the f
 ort parade ground.\n\n \n\nPhoto by Jairus Hill : Living historian demonstr
 ating a musket at Fort Macon State Park.
DTEND:20260801T183000Z
DTSTAMP:20260410T030933Z
DTSTART:20260801T143000Z
GEO:34.696366;-76.684506
LOCATION:Fort Macon State Park
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Small Arms Demonstration 10:30am & 2:30pm
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52019009724958
URL:https://events.dncr.nc.gov/event/small-arms-demonstration-1030am-230pm
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:NC Cultural Resources
CATEGORIES:Education Programs
DESCRIPTION:Pretend you’ve been recruited as a member of the Culper Spy Rin
 g\, and you need to know how to decipher a message written in invisible ink
 . Supplies include a paint brush\, water\, drying cloth\, vitriol (diluted 
 sulfuric acid)\, Thomas Jefferson cipher and “furnace box.” Read the clues 
 to find the coin with a hidden message\, reveal the message using the brush
  and vitriol\, then use the cipher to decode the message.\n\nContact: Nancy
  Locquet Absillis\, nancy.locquet@naturalsciences.org
DTSTAMP:20260410T030933Z
